\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
That woman? If you guessed Bathsheba you're right. David's whole life is turned upside because he was standing looking lustfully at another woman he shouldn't have. \
\
And that is how I've heard the story preached multiple times over the years. Adultery is bad, lust is bad, lust destroyed David's life, and it can destroy yours. And that is a true statement...it's just not the whole story. There is something more subtle going on in chapter 11 that is often missed.\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs38 \cf2 THE ONE YOU CAN'T SEE\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf2 \
The most dangerous alligator isn't the one you see and avoid, it's the one you don't know is there. It's the one lurking underneath the dark murky waters of our lives, waiting for us to relax and not pay attention. See, alligators are patient. They can sit underwater waiting for the right moment to strike. If you've ever watched a NatGeo special on animals and there is what appears to be animals drinking from a lake or pond and the water is still, there's a good chance that at any moment a gator is going to come up and bite whatever is foolish enough to drink from it's water source.  \
\
The story of David isn't about the very obvious issue of lust that plagued his life. I think David knew that about himself and probably protected himself from that one. The story of David is about a less visible, smaller and yet more destructive alligator in his life.  \
\
Chapter 11 starts off with what I call a throw away verse. Not that you should throw them away...but what we do is skip through certain verse and get to good ones...the important ones...the ones that 'preach' to our lives. The ones like David looking lustfully at a woman who was not his wife.\
\
But that first verse is everything. It is the hinge verse between David's good life and the rest of his life. It's so important I memorized it years ago so I wouldn't forget it. Here is what it says...\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf3 2 Samuel 11\
In the spring, at the time when kings go off to war, 
\f2\i David sent Joab out
\f1\i0  with the king\'92s men and the whole Israelite army. They destroyed the Ammonites and besieged Rabbah. 
\f2\i But David remained in Jerusalem
\f1\i0 . \cf0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Did you catch it? It's subtle but everything. At the time when kings were suppose to be going to war...David sent someone else to fight his own battles. I don't know WHY David did this. I could be he was tried and being lazy. It could have been he felt entitled as the king to not have to go out again, after all he had killed and fought many battles before, it could have been he just felt like he had something more important to do during that season. We don't know, but what we do know is that author is trying to tell us something about David's current state. David was not where he was suppose to be.\
\
When you know this it makes a little more sense maybe why Bathsheba was out bathing like that. The men were gone, or at least MOST of the men were gone. David finds himself in a place where not only does he want to sleep with a woman who is not his own, but her husband happens to be miles away. There is no accountability here for either her or him. \
\
And we know how the story goes right? He stays home and is not where he is suppose to be (feeds the small little gator). He walking around at night when most people are in bed (feeds the gator). He see's a beautiful woman naked taking a bath and instead of looking away to protect her dignity, he stares (feeds the gator). He then asks about her and who she is (feeds the gator). He then requests some time with her (feeds the gator) and eventually sleeps with her, gets her pregnant, and kill her current husband to protect himself from the shame and guilt of what he did. \
\
You know the rest of the story...the alligator of laziness fed over a short period of time has grown and bitten him. And when an alligator bites you, you're never the same. David's life ends tragically...all because of one small decision. A decision to stay home when he should have went out. A decision to feed into a small compromise that lead to great disaster.  \
\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 IF I COULD GO BACK\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
I have often wondered what David would have done if somehow he would have known what was at stake in that moment, would he have done the same thing? If some way he would have known all the pain, heartache, and suffering that would be caused by him taking a day off of work, would he make the same decision. I don't think he would. I don't think any of us would. \
\
Which is sort of the point. We don't see our lives in the future, we can only learn from the past.\
\
There are normally two types of people I do counseling with. The ones who have boundaries and excuses and reasons why they are not willing to make really hard sacrificial decision to fix their lives. These people have alligators but they're still somewhat in control of them. Something is happened which is why they are meeting with me but normally not it's not too bad. \
\
But in their mind, they are still in control. They are willing to feed whatever alligator has brought them to me because it really isn't that big...yet. \
\
Take a second now and go back to the list on page XX where I listed all the excuses of why we don't take alligators seriously? Think for a moment. Are you saying any of those to yourself or someone else who cares about you. Is there some lie you are tempted to believe because if you're honest, you don't it to be true because you still enjoy it, like it, need it in your life and can't imagine your life without it. \
\
Then there are the people who will do anything. They have been bitten, it has ruined their life, and now everything is on the table. Confession, boundaries, accountability, radical changes...whatever it takes. These people tend to have success. They embrace the way God designed them and imperfectly improve to the point where they are eventually free from whatever holds them back.\
\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 THE HORROR MOVIE PHENOMENON\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf0 \
Growing up my dad loved horror movies. Not sure why because I really can't stand them but we would watch all the classics. I would have nightmares, he would wonder why, it was a fun game we had. But if you've ever watched a horror movie you know at some point someone is going to make a ridiculously dumb decision. In fact it will be so dumb that you will instinctively know they are probably going to die. \
\
The examples are numerous but here are a few:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}It's the kids who go off alone to have sex or get drunk - they're not alone and are going to die. \
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}It's the person who want's split up and goes off alone - they won't be joining them again. \
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}It's the person who wants to see what that noise is in the basement or attic - the noise is going to kill them. \
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}The person who says "I'll be right back" - They won't be back.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}The person who reads the cursed book - they will be cursed (Guard your hear.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Going back for something or someone - they should have left them.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}The person who trusts the wrong people - Everyone else saw it but them.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
There have been times where people have yelled at the screen - what are you doing??? \
\
The same is true for a book or play or really anything we watch in life. When it doesn't have to do with us and we can be an impartial unbiased judge, many times it's obvious where the person is going and what will happen to them if they keep going.\
\
Maybe you are the type of person who everyone comes to for advice. In fact, you may even think you're pretty good at giving advice. You have the ability to hear a problem and just sort of know what they should do. You give some of the best relationship advice there is out there. \
\
And yet, you find yourself struggling with your own relationship issues. You can help others with their finances and hold them accountable but you're in so much debt. (I need some more example here maybe)\
\
The reason, when someone else tells us their problem it is like a movie or book being read out loud to us. Those same horror movies instincts we have kick in and we start to look at not what is happening but will eventually happen. The person telling the story is focused on the present, the person hearing the story is focusing on the tragectory. The person telling the story will talk about their heart, and intentions, and desires, and good motives. The person who hears the story knows that ultimatley none of those things matter. \
\
It's obvious because there is a script. Everyone follows a script. And the script is actually laid out for us in the book of James.\
In chapter 1 he says it this way:\
\
